itish and European audiences. The book aims to illustrate that British officers did not spend all their time oppressing and inferiorising the indigenous peoples under their colonial authority, but also contributed to propagating cultural and scientific information about them, and that they did not react only negatively to the various types of human difference they encountered in the field.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aStudies in Imperialism 2017. 7aHISTORY / Asia / India & South Asia.2bisacsh  aJames Tod.  abeyond binary oppositions.  afriendly exchanges.  ageographical moorings.  ahistory.  ainstitutional and ethnic hypotheses.  amaking Rajputana known.  amediator of knowledge.  asocial customs.  athe Rajputs.1 aD’Souza, Florence, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2015 eBook-Packagez978311128311140uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978178499207140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781784992071423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781784992071/original  a978-3-11-128311-1  Manchester University Press 2015 eBook-Packageb2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles